        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <em>
          Last week, I left out an unexpected detail out of my deep dive:
         </em>
         <em>
          Even
          <strong>
           Issac Newton
          </strong>
          couldn't resist a good meme stock.
         </em>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <em>
          In 1720, Newton's friends invested in the South Sea Trading Company (the GME of their day). But while his friends all got rich, he invested what would now be worth $4,000,000 at the top and lost it all in a week.
         </em>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <em>
          If Issac Newton could lose everything in the pursuit of riches, it could happen to anyone. That's why I make
          <strong>
           my portfolio
          </strong>
          \xe2\x80\x9c
          <strong>
           idiot-proof\xe2\x80\x9d with safe-haven assets with solid upside
          </strong>
          like fine art.
         </em>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <em>
          As an investment, art checks a lot of boxes:
